metadata.value: The main entrance to Edibrugh University Library, including sign and cement benches, as seen from street level in George Square. The purpose built Main Library, designed by Spence, Glover, and Ferguson was orginally opened in 1967 and the facade is designed to look like a bookcase. Each story is an acre in size, and at the time of opening the library was the largest university library in the UK. Since its opening the library has since undergone extensive rennovations to maximize its space and carry out essnetial upgrades including a the new Centre for Research Collections housed on the sixth floor, the upgrading of conservation and digital imaging studios, and more efficient shelving for general collections with those books in the lowest demand being moved offsite. The library now boasts a variety of services for teaching, learning, and research including conference rooms, technology suits, group and individual study spaces, a cafe and an exhibition hall.

canvases.label: Clement Littil 'Thair to Remain' Treasures room, CRC 5th Floor, December 2011.

metadata.value: The Treasures Room of the Centre for Research Collections, Edinburgh University Library
metadata.label: Title

metadata.value: The glass wall etched with the words of Clement Litill's 1580 bequest in the Centre for Research Collections closed access viewing room. The books contained in the room include those of Clement Litill, David Laing, James Cathcart White, and many others. The 'treasures room' is home to some of the rarest and most iconic items in the Special Collections holdings including the Incunables, Western Medieval Manuscripts, and Oriental Manuscripts. Such iconic items include the Celtic Psalter (Ms 56), the Rashid al-Din (Or.Ms 20), and the Laing charters are housed behind this wall.
